				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$i_{\mathrm{c}}{\mathrm{ = \nu C}}_{{\mathrm{DL}}},$$\end{document}where ν is the scan rate. The slope of the plot of ic as a function of ν is equal to CDL.

The ECSA is calculated from the double layer capacitance according to:2ECSA =CDL∕Cs,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{ECSA = }}C_{{\mathrm{DL}}}{\mathrm{/}}C_{\mathrm{s}},$$\end{document}where Cs is the specific capacitance of the sample. We use general specific capacitances of Cs = 0.035 mF cm−2 based on typical reported values. The roughness factor (RF) is then calculated by dividing ECSA by 0.07065 cm2, the geometric area of the electrode.

